On day seven, I learnt about collision domains and broadcast domains in networking. The lesson focused on how network traffic behaves within a network and the methods used to reduce congestion and improve communication efficiency.

Topics Covered and What I Learnt
1. Collision Domains

I learnt that a collision domain is a network segment where data collisions can occur when multiple devices attempt to send data at the same time. I understood that:

Older network devices such as hubs create a single collision domain
Switches reduce collisions by creating separate collision domains for each port
Full-duplex communication helps eliminate collisions

This topic helped me understand how switches improve network performance compared to hubs.

2. Broadcast Domains

I learnt that a broadcast domain is a group of devices that receive broadcast messages sent by one device within the network. I understood that:

Routers separate broadcast domains
Switches forward broadcast traffic within the same VLAN
Large broadcast domains can increase unnecessary network traffic

This helped me understand how broadcasts affect network efficiency and performance.

3. Alleviate Network Congestion

I learnt different methods used to reduce network congestion and improve communication efficiency. These methods included:

Using switches instead of hubs
Segmenting networks with VLANs
Reducing unnecessary broadcast traffic
Implementing proper network design
Using routers to divide broadcast domains

I understood that proper network segmentation improves speed, stability, and overall performance.

4. Check Your Understanding – Switching Domains

Finally, I completed an activity to test my understanding of switching domains. The exercise helped me:

Differentiate between collision domains and broadcast domains
Analyse how switches and routers manage traffic
Understand how network devices reduce congestion

This activity strengthened my understanding of network segmentation and efficient traffic management within modern networks.
